  "text": "The key difficulty of computing the objective function value or its gradient lies in the exponential cardinality of Y. When the underlying structure of Y is a linear chain or a tree, both objective function values and its gradient can be efficiently computed by dynamic programming method (the Viterbi algorithm [CITATION_1] ). In this case, a number of methods could be used to solve (10), for example, deterministic methods such as the iterative scaling algorithm in [CITATION_2] , L-BFGS [CITATION_3] , stochastic methods such as SGD in [CITATION_4] and SAG in [CITATION_5] . However, the computational issue of CRF has not been fully addressed when the underlying structure is more complex. In our setting, we can formulate (10) as a composition optimization problem as in (4) by noticing that (10) is equivalent to",
